            "language": "markdown",
            "source": [
                "Variables"
            ],
            "outputs": []
        },
        {
            "language": "typescript",
            "source": [
                "// \"declaration\" means creating a variable without assigning a value to it.\r\nvar a;\r\n// \"assignment\" means giving a value to a declared variable.\r\na = 10;\r\n// \"Reassignment\" refers to changing the value of an already declared variable.\r\na = 20;\r\n// \"redeclaration\" means declaring a variable with the same name again and its overiding the previous value.\r\nvar a = 30; \r\n// \"declaration\" + \"assignment\" = \"initialization\", while \"initialization\" means creating a variable and assigning a value to it at the same time.\r\nvar b = 5;\r\n// \"redeclaration\" means declaring a variable with the same name again in the same scope,it allowed in JavaScript, but it can lead to confusion and bugs, so it's generally recommended to avoid it.\r\nvar b = 15;\r\n//output printing\r\nconsole.log(a, b);"
            ],
            "outputs": [
                {
                    "items": [
                        {
                            "mime": "application/vnd.code.notebook.stdout",
                            "value": [
                                "20 15",
                                "",
                                ""
                            ]
                        }
                    ]
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "language": "typescript",
            "source": [
                "// types variables declaration\r\nvar y; // This will not throw an error because 'var' variables \"can\" be declared without initialization.\r\n\r\n\r\nlet x; // This will not throw an error because 'let' variables \"can\" be declared without initialization.\r\n\r\n\r\nconst z = 30; // This will throw an error because 'const' variables must be initialized at the time of declaration. and const \"cannot\" be declared without initialization.\r\n\r\n\r\n// \"***assignment***\"\r\nvar y = 100; //var variables \"****can be reassigned and redeclared.****\"\r\n\r\nx = 50; //let variables \"****can be reassigned but not redeclared.****\"\r\n\r\n// \"**const z = 40;**\"\" // This will throw an error because 'const' variables cannot be reassigned.\"****const z= 30 must me initialized at the time of declaration.and once initialized, cannot be changed.****\"\r\n\r\n\r\nconsole.log(y, x, z);"
            ],
            "outputs": [
                {
                    "items": [
                        {
                            "mime": "application/vnd.code.notebook.stdout",
                            "value": [
                                "100 50 30",
                                "",
                                ""
                            ]
                        }
                    ]
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "language": "typescript",
            "source": [
                "//if  checks condition and executes the block of code if the condition is true. In this case, the condition is always true, because of \"true is keyword\",so the block of code will always execute.\r\nif (true) {\r\n\r\n    var k = 1;\r\n\r\n    let i = 2;\r\n\r\n    const t = 3;\r\n}\r\n\r\nconsole.log(k); // works\r\n\r\nconsole.log(i); // error\r\n\r\nconsole.log(t); // error"
            ],
